The paper discusses the potential threats and security implications of WebGL, which falls under the category of computer graphics (cs.GR) and computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the practical aspects of successful attacks, such as stealthiness and user-experience, which falls under the category of software engineering (cs.SE). The paper also discusses the use of distributed attacks, which falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). Finally, the paper discusses the implementation of a Chrome extension for detecting and blocking WebGL, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
